measures.name: set_space_infiltration_by_exterior_surface_area
measures.display_name: Set Space Infiltration by Exterior Surface Area
measures.description:
Replace all Space Infiltration objects with a new one that has a prescribed flow rate per exterior surface area.  There are many strategies that can be used to reduce infiltration.

Seal Windows ? Seal all windows and doors with weather strip and fill any air gaps with insulation and caulking to prevent air infiltration.

Install Revolving Doors on the Inner Door Entrance - Replace the high traffic entrance doors with revolving doors.  This will reduce the air infiltration associated with the doors.  Notice that loading dock doors and handicapped accessible entrances cannot be replaced with revolving doors.

Install an Air Curtain for the Loading Dock Door - An air curtain should be installed in the entryway of loading dock doors.  This will greatly reduce outside air from infiltrating during periods of time when loading dock doors are open.

Identify and seal other sources of infiltration ? Look for other uncontrolled infiltration sources and work to air seal.  These could be former electrical chases, abandoned HVAC ducting, general envelope deterioration, or many other sources.
measures.modeler_description:
Remove all infiltration objects used in the model and add in a new object to each space type, and then to spaces without space types. Schedules come from the schedule sets. Warn user if there is no schedule set associated with a space type.

A one time material & installation cost can be added to the building object to reflect improvements made throughout the envelope. "Years Until Costs Start? is typically "0?, but you can use a larger number if you want to delay the improvements.  O&M cost and frequency can be whatever is appropriate for the component. This measure hard sizes the costs based on current infiltration levels.  As a result any change to the models made by measures run after this that have an impact on infiltration will not affect the cost. An example of a problematic measure would be deleting a space from the model or making each floor taller; in both cases adjusting the total exterior envelope area.

measures.description: This measure removes all existing electric equipment from spaces recognized as office building space types. New electric objects will be added based on the 50% Small to Medium Office AEDG recommendations.
measures.modeler_description: Equipment in un-recognized spaces will be left alone. This measure will attempt to retain schedules from the initial model. If the initial model contained multiple electric equipment objects associated with multiple schedules, then one of those schedules will be picked for the new electric equipment.

measures.name: aedg_small_to_medium_office_electric_equipment_controls
measures.description: This measure reduces the values associated with electric equipment schedules to simulate reductions due to equipment controls throughout the building. This includes occupancy based outlets or adapters, as well as network or timer based controls.
measures.modeler_description: This measure is intended to be used on schedules that have not previously been adjusted for advanced controls. If you run this measure multiple times you will end up with more schedule reduction than is appropriate. The schedules used in the OpenStudio templates have not been adjusted for advanced controls, so it is appropriate to run them through this measure to simulation their impact on energy use. This measure applies a reduction of 0.1 to schedule values that are below 0.5 start with, and a reduction of 0.05 to values that are at or above 0.5 to start with. As a result the lower the initial fractional value the higher the percentage reduction it will receive. This results on more a higher percentage reduction in un-occupied hours vs. occupied hours. Values won't be lowered to a value below 0.1. Values already below this level will keep their original value.

measures.name: aedg_small_to_medium_office_fenestration_and_daylighting_controls
measures.description: This measure will remove all existing exterior windows, glass doors, and skylights from your model. They will be replaced with view and daylight windows as recommended by the Small to Medium Office AEDG recommendations. Windows on the south facade will have a exterior shading or light shelf surfaces depending on if they are view or daylight windows. East and west view windows will have internal shading controls. In spaces with daylighting controls daylight sensor will be added. The modeler should inspect where the sensors were placed, the recommended illuminance setpoint, and the fraction of the zones lighting controlled by the sensor.
measures.modeler_description: This measure is intended for use in models created form space types defined in the office building types. Fenestration will be added to all spaces with exterior walls except for spaces not included in the floor area. This should include attic and plenum spaces. Daylighting will only be added to north and south facades. North and south facades can be +/- 30 degrees of north and south. East and west facades will only receive view windows. The daylight sensor's depth in from the wall will typically be the same as the height of the wall that the daylight windows is on. This depth is also what is used to calculate the daylight fraction of the space. In spaces that are non convex, such as an L shaped space, we may not be able to place a sensor, if that happens a warning will be issued.

measures.name: aedg_small_to_medium_office_exterior_wall_construction
measures.description: This measure will modify existing exterior wall insulation levels based on construction type and climate zone. The exterior wall construction type and climate zone should be set in the model prior to using this measure. For mass and metal walls if an existing insulation layer can be found it will be increased, if not a new insulation layer will be added. For mass this will be at the exterior of the construction. For metal it will be added just behind the exterior layer. For steel and wood framed walls, insulation will be added to the exterior of the construction.

measures.name: aedg_small_to_medium_office_interior_finishes
measures.description: This measure will adjust the visible reflectance of materials used on interior building surfaces. Different target values will be set for floors, ceilings, and furniture/interior partition surfaces.
measures.modeler_description: While the AEDG guide recommends unique wall reflectance targets above and below 7', the measure will use the 7' target on all interior walls. Cost was not included as part of this measure as there likely isn't a significant cost impact to lighter finishes. This measure will treat interior partition surfaces as furniture. The measure will only enhance reflectance. If a material already exceeds the target it will be left alone. Optionally you can also lower selected interior partition surfaces to 36".

measures.name: aedg_small_to_medium_office_exterior_lighting
measures.description: This measure will create exterior lights objects in four different categories described below. The lighting levels and controls will be based on the "How to Implement Recommendations" section in the AEDG; any existing exterior lighting will be removed. A special input is needed for this measure to define the exterior lighting zone, which further describes whether the site is urban or rural.
measures.modeler_description:
Provide an area or dimensions as input for each of the exterior lighting categories described below. 
- Facade and landscape lighting
- Parking lots and drives
- Walkways, plaza, and special features areas
- All other exterior lighting
    
Lighting Zones:
0 - Undeveloped areas within national parks, state parks, forest land, rural areas, and other undeveloped areas as defined by the authority having jurisdiction (no lighting recommendations)
1 - Developed areas of national parks, state parks, forest land, and rural areas (no lighting recommendations)
2 - Areas predominantly consisting of residential zoning, neighborhood business districts, light industrial with limited nighttime use and residential mixed use areas
3 - All other areas
4 - High activity commercial districts in major metropolitan areas as designated by the local jurisdiction

measures.name: openstudio_results
measures.description: This measure creates high level tables and charts pulling both from model inputs and EnergyPlus results. It has building level information as well as detail on space types, thermal zones, HVAC systems, envelope characteristics, and economics. Click the heading above a chart to view a table of the chart data.
measures.modeler_description: For the most part consumption data comes from the tabular EnergyPlus results, however there are a few requests added for time series results. Space type and loop details come from the OpenStudio model. The code for this is modular, making it easy to use as a template for your own custom reports. The structure of the report uses bootstrap, and the graphs use dimple js.

measures.name: envelope_and_internal_load_breakdown
measures.description: Report provides annual and monthly views into heat gains and losses for envelope and internal loads.
measures.modeler_description: It uses the following variables: Electric Equipment Total Heating Energy, Zone Lights Total Heating Energy, Zone, People Sensible Heating Energy, Surface Average Face Conduction Heat Transfer Energy, Surface Window Heat Gain Energy, Surface Window Heat Loss Energy, Zone Infiltration Sensible Heat Gain Energy, Zone Infiltration Sensible Heat Loss Energy. For Surface Average Face Conduction Heat Transfer Energy bin positive values as heat gain and negative values as heat loss.
